      "rationale": "These methods form a cohesive marker management system that maintains collections of markers organized by type, layer, and index. Extracting them into a MarkerRegistry improves separation of concerns by isolating all marker-related operations and state management from the main plotting logic, while providing a clean registry interface for marker lifecycle operations.",
      "reasoning": "\nStep 1: Primary Responsibility Analysis\nThese methods share a single, well-defined responsibility: managing markers on a plot. They handle the complete lifecycle of markers including adding, removing, clearing, and retrieving markers. All operations are focused on organizing markers by type (domain/range), layer (foreground/background), and index, while maintaining proper event listener relationships.\n\nStep 2: Shared Concept/Domain\nAll methods belong to the \"marker management\" domain within charting. They operate exclusively on the four marker-related Map fields and implement a consistent pattern for marker operations. The methods represent a cohesive subsystem that encapsulates all marker-related state and behavior, including listener management and change notifications.\n\nStep 3: Extraction Benefits\n- Single Responsibility Principle: Isolates marker management from other plotting concerns\n- Reduces Complexity: Removes 20+ methods from the XYPlot god class, making it more focused\n- Improves Testability: Marker operations can be tested independently of plot rendering logic\n- Enhances Reusability: Marker management logic could potentially be reused by other plot types\n- Better Encapsulation: All marker-related state and operations are contained in one cohesive unit\n\nStep 4: Design Justification\nThis follows the Extract Class refactoring pattern to separate concerns. The extracted class will have high cohesion (all methods manage markers) and low coupling (minimal dependencies beyond Marker objects and change notifications). It represents a classic example of the Single Responsibility Principle by isolating marker collection management.\n",
